07723nam a22009375i 9780857457417DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574574177 a10.1515/97808574574172doi  a(DE-B1597)636522  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN635.E18bW56 2015 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a305.8009522300aWind Over Water :bMigration in an East Asian Context /ced. by David W. Haines, Keiko Yamanaka, Shinji Yamashita. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aASAO Studies in Pacific Anthropology ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Migrants, States, and Cities -- tChapter 1 Human Trade in Colonial Vietnam -- tChapter 2 Wind through the Woods: Ethnography of Interfaces between Migration and Institutions -- tChapter 3 Migrant Social Networks: Ethnic Minorities in the Cities of China -- tChapter 4 Migration and DiverseCity: Singapore’s Changing Demography, Identity, and Landscape -- tChapter 5 A Transnational Community and Its Impact on Local Power Relations in Urban China: The Case of Beijing’s “Koreatown” in the Early 2000s -- tChapter 6 Immigration, Policies, and Civil Society in Hamamatsu, Central Japan -- tPart II: Family, Gender, Lifestyle, and Culture -- tChapter 7 Multiple Narratives on Migration in Vietnam and Their Methodological Implications -- tChapter 8 Cross-Border Marriages between Vietnamese Women and Chinese Men: The Integration of Otherness and the Impact of Popular Representations -- tChapter 9 Achieving and Restoring Masculinity through Homeland Return Visits -- tChapter 10 Mothers on the Move: Transnational Child-Rearing by Japanese Women Married to Pakistani Migrants -- tChapter 11 Here, There, and In-between: Lifestyle Migrants from Japan -- tChapter 12 Moving and Touring in Time and Place: Korean National History Tourism to Northeast China -- tPart III: Work, Ethnicity, and Nationality -- tChapter 13 In the Shadows and at the Margins: Working in the Korean Clubs and Bars of Osaka’s Minami Area -- tChapter 14 African Traders in Chungking Mansions, Hong Kong -- tChapter 15 Negotiating “Home” and “Away”: Singaporean Professional Migrants in China -- tChapter 16 “Guarded Globalization”: The Politics of Skill Recognition on Migrant Health Care Workers -- tConclusion -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProviding a comprehensive treatment of a full range of migrant destinies in East Asia by scholars from both Asia and North America, this volume captures the way migrants are changing the face of Asia, especially in cities, such as Beijing, Hong Kong, Hamamatsu, Osaka, Tokyo, and Singapore. It investigates how the crossing of geographical boundaries should also be recognized as a crossing of cultural and social categories that reveals the extraordinary variation in the migrants’ origins and trajectories. These migrants span the spectrum: from Korean bar hostesses in Osaka to African entrepreneurs in Hong Kong, from Vietnamese women seeking husbands across the Chinese border to Pakistani Muslim men marrying women in Japan, from short-term business travelers in China to long-term tourists from Japan who ultimately decide to retire overseas. Illuminating the ways in which an Asian-based analysis of migration can yield new data on global migration patterns, the contributors provide important new theoretical insights for a broader understanding of global migration, and innovative methodological approaches to the spatial and temporal complexity of human migration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, vi